1. kubectl get nodes: The command kubectl get nodes lists all the nodes (machines) in a Kubernetes cluster along with their status, roles, age, and Kubernetes version.
    Nodes are the workers in a Kubernetes cluster: Pods run on nodes, If a node is unhealthy, applications may fail, Cluster troubleshooting usually starts here.
    This command helps you: Verify cluster connectivity, Check node health, See how many nodes you have, Confirm worker vs control‑plane nodes.
    ✅ Show more details: kubectl get nodes -o wide
    ✅ Describe a specific node (deep debugging):  kubectl describe node <node-name>
    ✅ Filter by labels: kubectl get nodes --show-labels

    🔹 Real‑World Scenarios: run the command in below scenarios
        ✅ After cluster creation
        ✅ Application not scheduling
        ✅ After adding nodes

        nodes = machines
        pods  = workloads. smallest deployable unit

2. kubectl get pods -A
    It shows every running (or stopped) Pod in the entire cluster, not just in your current namespace. -A means All namespaces (same as --all-namespaces).
    🔹 Why -A Is Important: By default, Kubernetes commands operate in one namespace only (usually default).
        kubectl get pods                 // shows pods only in the current namespace
     kubectl get pods -A -o wide         // shows more details
    ✅ Filter by namespace:               kubectl get pods -n kube-system
    ✅ Find failing pods :                kubectl get pods -A | grep -v Running
    ✅ Check only specific namespaces:    kubectl get pods -n default

    🔹 Real‑World Troubleshooting Example
        ❌ Application is not accessible.
        Steps:
            1. kubectl get pods -A

3. kubectl config get-contexts
     It tells you which clusters, users, and namespaces your kubectl can connect to, and which one is active right now and configured in your kubeconfig file.
     🔹 Why this command is important: In real‑world Kubernetes usage you often work with:
        multiple clusters (dev / qa / prod)
        multiple cloud providers (GKE / EKS / AKS / On‑prem)
        multiple users or service accounts
    This command helps you: avoid operating in the wrong cluster, verify your current kubectl context, safely switch between environments.
    ⚠️ Many production incidents happen because someone ran a command in the wrong context.
    ✅ kubectl commands always run in the active context unless overridden. 
    🔹 What is a Kubernetes Context?
        A context is a combination of:
            Cluster → where the API server is
            User → who you are
            Namespace → default scope
    🔹 Switch to a Different Context:    kubectl config use-context prod-context
        Verify:                           kubectl config current-context
    🔹 Use Context Temporarily (Safe Practice):   kubectl --context=qa-context get pods
            ✅ Avoids accidental changes
            ✅ Recommended for production operations
    🔹 Real‑World Scenario: You intend to scale a deployment in dev, but accidentally scale prod.
            ✅ First thing to check:    kubectl config get-contexts
            ✅ Confirm active context before executing commands.

4.  What is a Namespace?
    A namespace is a Kubernetes resource used to logically isolate workloads inside a single cluster. 
    What namespaces control?
        Resource names (can repeat across namespaces)
        Access control (RBAC)
        Quotas & limits
        Resource organization (dev, qa, prod)

    ✅ Common namespaces:  kubectl get namespaces
        output: default, kube-system, kube-public, monitoring, prod.


